(1) Wind and Solar Overtake Coal Power for First Time in U.S. [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/7ea0fd26-0c58-4eb7-9161-db7d9c13002e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Perry Cleveland-Peck for WSJ
Wind and solar energy generated more electricity in the U.S. than coal for =
the first time last year, according to analysis from clean-energy think tan=
k Ember. The two renewable energy sources accounted for 17% of the country=
=E2=80=99s power mix while coal fell to a low of 15%, it said.
For the first time ever, wind and solar energy outproduced coal in the U.S.=
, supplying 17% of the country=E2=80=99s electricity compared to coal=E2=80=
=99s 15%. Solar led the charge, growing 27% year-over-year, and even outpac=
ed natural gas in meeting new demand. The US installed over 50 gigawatts of=
 solar in 2024, with Texas and California leading the way. This solar build=
out was largely made possible by the plummeting costs of solar panels over =
the last decade, with costs down nearly 90%.=20
Replacing coal with renewables is an undeniable good. Coal is a highly poll=
utive and emits massive amounts of carbon dioxide, sulfur dioxide, and part=
iculate matter. It=E2=80=99s also dangerous to mine and can pollute the env=
ironment around the mines. Coal is no bueno, especially when compared to th=
e other energy sources at our disposal.=20
More energy is good. The more of it that=E2=80=99s clean and cheap, the bet=
ter. For the US and the world to progress, the goal isn=E2=80=99t just redu=
cing coal consumption. It=E2=80=99s generating abundant, cheap and relative=
ly clean energy with lots and lots of solar, wind, nuclear, and, at least f=
or the time being, oil and LNG.=20
(2) How Natural Gas Became America=E2=80=99s Most Important Export [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/c52cc6a8-6d5c-480c-b92f-93382840f1d4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Kevin Crowley and Ruth Liao for Bloomberg
The US, which in the span of about seven years transformed itself from an i=
rrelevant supplier of LNG into the world=E2=80=99s largest, is set to expan=
d its production capacity by 60% in the first half of Donald Trump=E2=80=99=
s second presidency, according to an estimate from BloombergNEF. By the end=
 of the decade, almost 1 in every 3 tankers carrying the superchilled fuel =
will originate in the US=E2=80=A6
LFG, LNG!
A decade ago, back in 2015, the U.S. was a minor player in the liquefied na=
tural gas (LNG) market. Today, the U.S. is the world=E2=80=99s largest expo=
rter of LNG and has plans to expand that lead over the coming years. This t=
ransition to LNG super-producer has shifted the way the country interacts w=
ith global energy markets and transformed our entire approach to geopolitic=
s.=20
This is how it happened:
Fracking =E2=80=93 Tech advances, like horizontal drilling, unlocked massiv=
e shale gas reserves.
Infrastructure =E2=80=93 Companies built massive LNG plants to liquefy and =
ship gas worldwide.
Global Demand =E2=80=93 Europe needed a Russia alternative, Asia needed fue=
l, and the U.S. was ready to supply.
Policy =E2=80=93 Trump lifted export limits and Biden sent LNG to Europe
And while LNG is still a fossil fuel, it has some key advantages to other f=
ossil fuels and renewables. It=E2=80=99s cleaner than coal & oil and more r=
eliable and scalable than renewables. In a perfect world 10 to 20 years fro=
m now, would we want to totally replace LNG with renewables? Of course. But=
 as we build towards a cleaner energy future, the U.S. is extremely advanta=
ged to bridge that gap with LNG.
(3) NASA Launches Missions to Study Sun, Universe=E2=80=99s Beginning [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/5bc91bb3-d2d0-457f-ada5-fb87239c61ec?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From NASA
NASA=E2=80=99s newest astrophysics observatory, SPHEREx, is on its way to s=
tudy the origins of our universe and the history of galaxies, and to search=
 for the ingredients of life in our galaxy.
Two missions for the price of one rocket launch.
Earlier this week, NASA NASA launched both the SPHEREx and PUNCH missions a=
board a SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket. SPHEREx will map the entire sky every six m=
onths using spectroscopy to study the origins of the universe, galaxy forma=
tion, and the building blocks of life. PUNCH, a set of four small satellite=
s, will observe the Sun=E2=80=99s outer atmosphere and solar wind to improv=
e understanding of space weather.
Both missions are live, having established communications and are now enter=
ing their respective commissioning phases. SPHEREx=E2=80=99s data will comp=
lement existing telescopes like James Webb, while PUNCH will help predict s=
olar storms that impact Earth.
These specific missions aside, it=E2=80=99s really cool to watch momentum p=
ick up in space. Writing a newsletter that covers these types of stories ma=
kes that momentum all the more obvious. It seems like every week now there=
=E2=80=99s a new NASA mission or SpaceX milestone or startup breakthrough.
(4): This is Gavin Newsom [ https://substack.com/redirect/f2bdbf66-9882-440=
7-85bd-34bfa975f0bf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Yes, Gavin Newsom launching a podcast made this week=E2=80=99s list of top =
optimistic stories. Hear me out.
I=E2=80=99ll be honest: I am not a fan of Gavin Newsom. I don=E2=80=99t par=
ticularly like Charlie Kirk. And I=E2=80=99m certainly not a Steve Bannon g=
uy. But what I do like is bipartisan dialogue and engagement, especially in=
 long form podcasts.=20
Coming out of the 2024 elections, it was clear that the Democrats =E2=80=94=
 as silly as this might sound =E2=80=94 had a podcast problem. The medium w=
as dominated by right wing/conservative/Trump-supporting hosts, and those h=
osts were often visited by Republican politicians that were willing and abl=
e to engage in multi-hour, unscripted conversations. Not only does appearin=
g on podcasts with millions of listeners for three hours make you more nota=
ble, but for skilled politicians, it provides the opportunity to explain yo=
ur ideas in a compelling manner and connect with the audience on a deeper l=
evel. We saw this with the Trump children on Lex, JD Vance on Rogan, and Tr=
ump on Theo Von.=20
 The Democrats did not have the same roster of friendly podcasts hosts =E2=
=80=94 Kamala ended up tapping Alex Cooper of Call Her Daddy for her first =
~longish podcast of the campaign =E2=80=94 and did not have the roster of p=
oliticians that were willing and able to engage in more casual, long-form d=
iscussion. As an example, ahead of the election, the Dems sent John Fetterm=
an on Rogan, the guy who (to no fault of his own) can barely communicate. A=
nd sending Mayor Pete on The Daily does not exactly bring new folks into th=
e tent.
This problem was, and now certainly is, obvious to the Democrats. They=E2=
=80=99ve been searching for an answer to =E2=80=9CWho is the Left=E2=80=99s=
 Joe Rogan?=E2=80=9D since before the election. And, for better or worse, t=
he Left=E2=80=99s new Joe Rogan is=E2=80=A6Gavin Newsom? Do I think this sh=
ow will have a major impact on Newsom or Democratic politics? Probably not.=
 But do I think the Left trying to engage in more honest, authentic, long f=
orm conversation is a good thing for American politics? Absolutely. The par=
ty=E2=80=99s ideas are in desperate need of sunlight =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s=
 the strongest disinfectant =E2=80=94 and they=E2=80=99ve been stuck in the=
 cool shade of 3 minute CNN spots and overly accommodating Crooked Media in=
terviews.
And why is the Democratic party getting their shit together a good thing? I=
s it because I am a big lib that wants to see Democrats dominate elections =
and shape culture and control policy? Certainly not. But I do fear that, at=
 this current point in time, Republicans are starting to pull away with it =
=E2=80=94 demographic changes, blue state exoduses, anti-woke sentiments, e=
tc etc. And when any one party starts to run away with it, we start to see =
very shitty ideas become very shitty policies. So yes, I want a stronger De=
mocratic party right now. And that, believe it or not, starts with Gavin Ne=
wsom apologizing on his podcast for his Covid reservation at The French Lau=
ndry.
(5): Arc Boat, Aalo, Base Power Company, Pipedream, Too Cheap to Meter, and=
 Fuse
Packy here. This week, I went down to Austin and up to Montreal to spend ti=
me with some Vertical Integrators generating, storing, and taking advantage=
 of cheap, clean electricity, and to watch a documentary about how we can a=
chieve the holy grail of producing energy too cheap to meter. I am fired up=
=2E=20
On Tuesday, I kicked off the day with a ride on Arc=E2=80=99s [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/1e6f32fd-cb71-478f-a33b-db32e807b742?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] insanely cool Arc Sport. =
Before I went out, Arc=E2=80=99s CEO Mitch Lee told me that the difference =
between an electric boat and a gas boat was bigger than the difference betw=
een an electric car and a gas car. I didn=E2=80=99t get that until I was on=
 it; then I got it. It whips, and it=E2=80=99s incredibly fun to drive.
Fresh off the boat, I headed to visit Matt Loszak [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/08115983-4944-4365-ab82-92ef9a89f0dc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] at Aalo Atomics [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/c13ee3a1-201c-4f08-8dab-a355a294e32a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to check out the facility where t=
hey=E2=80=99re going to be manufacturing lots and lots of nuclear right her=
e in the US of A, starting with a =E2=80=9C50 MWe power plant purpose-built=
 for data centers.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99ve already begun: this picture is =
me and Matt next to the pressure vessel that Aalo made in the facility.
After that, I grabbed coffee with Garrett McCurrach [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/6b25aadb-4ec1-484a-a1ab-bc93fa60989d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the CEO of our portfolio company P=
ipedream Labs, which is building a hyperlogistics network underground [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/6b25aadb-4ec1-484a-a1ab-bc93fa60989d?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] (click the link, =
read the thread, it=E2=80=99s wild).=20
That night, I went to the screening of Jason Carman=E2=80=99s new Frontier =
Film: Too Cheap to Meter, put on by our friends at the Abundance Institute =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/7375e569-abd6-4fdf-b982-60aa839decd3?j=3Dey=
J1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. As we=E2=80=
=99ve talked about a thousand times in this newsletter, there=E2=80=99s not=
hing more important to civilization than energy production. Jason does a ch=
aracteristically excellent job telling that story through the people and co=
mpanies building the good future. He=E2=80=99s doing a screening in SF this=
 weekend, and if you=E2=80=99re around, you should 100% go [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/8f8f73d4-48e4-466e-8d24-506c576ac8aa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
On Wednesday, I spent the whole day at Base Power Company=E2=80=99s [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/4b489606-6cfb-4240-baa4-01c0784c9825?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] HQ to hang out with=
 a bunch of the team, see the batteries, and feel the =E2=80=A6 energy in p=
erson. If you=E2=80=99re not familiar with Base Power, you will be soon, an=
d I wrote about them last year [ https://substack.com/redirect/db7e354d-9eb=
2-490b-9fa6-53e000922506?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to get you up to speed. More to come=E2=80=A6=20
To top it all off, yesterday morning, I flew to Montreal to watch another p=
ortfolio company, Fuse [ https://substack.com/redirect/3650ebb0-8c5f-4156-8=
84f-b258d06ad7b6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] (Deep Dive here [ https://substack.com/redirect/6a631ba8-671c-42=
75-90d8-8d33bcdee417?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), successfully test fire its TITAN Impendence-Matched Marx G=
enerator, an important step towards both selling radiation-as-a-service and=
, eventually, selling fusion power to the grid. Watch it here [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/cf4ce05f-34ab-4b48-a8fe-dd59f839f5ed?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and here [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/0d292d4c-db30-47b5-b7d4-dcdb9d683a79?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
A few things struck me after spending time with all of these teams:=20
They=E2=80=99re very real. It=E2=80=99s one thing to read about a pulsed po=
wer generator. It=E2=80=99s a whole =E2=80=98nother thing to see it up clos=
e and personal, to watch it charge up its capacitors, and release oodles of=
 energy on a target. In the facility, it doesn=E2=80=99t feel like a scienc=
e project but an engineering and manufacturing one. Aalo is making actual r=
eactors. Base Power Company is installing batteries on real peoples=E2=80=
=99 homes every day. Pipedream is out there laying that pipe. And you can a=
ctually ride on and buy an Arc Boat and feel the difference between gas and=
 electric for yourself. All of these companies sound very cool, but I don=
=E2=80=99t think people fully realize that they=E2=80=99re actually happeni=
ng. These are businesses.=20
The future is electric. An electric boat just performs better than a gas bo=
at - it=E2=80=99s quiet, fast, turns on a dime, is a breeze to dock, and ge=
ts better with every software update. Our things will be delivered to us in=
 minutes under our feet via electric robots in pipes. Tons of entrepreneurs=
 =E2=80=94 the ones I met with and the ones Jason featured in the documenta=
ry =E2=80=94 are working on generating, transmitting, storing, and discharg=
ing megawatts, then gigawatts, then terawatts of sweet sweet power. I think=
 it=E2=80=99s still underappreciated how electric the future will be, and w=
hat that will mean for the quality of products and experiences humans have =
access to. It also means a whole new toolkit for people who want to rebuild=
 the world.=20
It=E2=80=99s really fun. Working on really hard, important problems with re=
ally smart, motivated people is as good as it gets. The vibes in each of th=
ese offices and facilities are excellent. If you=E2=80=99re thinking about =
what to do with your life, I couldn=E2=80=99t recommend looking at these co=
mpanies=E2=80=99 jobs pages more strongly.=20
What a week for the optimists.=20
BONUS: TBPN [ https://substack.com/redirect/b1b64178-c8b7-4fa3-b082-93ac7b7=
d8f72?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Anytime I have the excuse to pump the Technology Brothers, I will. They=E2=
=80=99re building the ESPN for startups, starting with daily 3 hour long st=
reams and call-ins. Think of it like (and I mean really visualize it) Howar=
d Stern, Bill Simmons, Jim Kramer and Jason Calacanis banging each other an=
d having the cutest little media baby. That=E2=80=99s TBPN.
ESPN changed sports. Suddenly sports became a 24/7 spectacle. Being a sport=
s fan no longer meant watching every game. It meant watching the pre and po=
st game coverage, consuming hours of analysis, debating that analysis with =
your friends, and getting to know the stories behind the teams. ESPN raised=
 the profile of sports: more athletes became celebrities, more people cared=
 and cared deeply about sports, and sports became more culturally relevant.=
 Startups deserve their own version of ESPN. With think John and Jordy can =
deliver that.
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
Thanks to HubSpot [ https://substack.com/redirect/a5580d8e-7a77-4b8c-b3b7-b=
dc96193df96?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for sponsoring! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox next week.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

